How Do You Think Technology Affects Dating?

Have you had any experience with dating? Have you ever used dating apps? If so, what has it been like for you? If not, why not?

How do you think technology — like apps, Netflix, social media and texting — affects dating and relationships? In your opinion, does it improve or worsen romantic interactions? How so?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It promotes a superficial and shallow view of people as commodities.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Rather than seeing people as complex and wonderful, we are presented with a limited and basic message that says, "here is what I'm good for."

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It promotes a shallowness in which we can glance over the person and make a judgment of them based on their profile picture, or how they present

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We lose opportunities to have real, meaningful, in-depth relationships where we can get to know someone in the "slow lane".

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Taking time to get to know someone is more meaningful than simply swiping right or left on a dating app.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Technology also encourages dishonesty and being manipulative, especially with how easy it is to delete or avoid people on social media and dating apps.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Technology seems to replace real, deep relationships with superficial ones.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Because there is such a rapid decline in value of one's interactions on social media, one spends more time on it and less time searching for a real

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: A lot of people act like movie characters, piecing together a picture of themselves that they wish was true, rather than expressing who they truly are.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: A lot of people seem to be on the hunt for perfection in the things and people they idolize.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: They are constantly comparing others to a perfect image they have created in their minds or a standard they've set.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: On social media and dating apps, you see constant comparisons and negativity.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Nothing is ever good enough, or someone is always doing better than you.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We focus on finding attention, likes, good pics-instead of finding real, meaningful people to relate to.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It's no wonder why there's an increase in anxiety and depression.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We are so far removed from natural human contact, and our sense of security and well being are suffering because of it.
